Problem Statement

Classification Problem

Fit two separate classification models to a dataset.
Create a confusion matrix for each model using three different cutoff values.
Generate an ROC curve and calculate the AUC for each model.

Regression Problem

Fit two separate regression models to a dataset (split into test and train). Find the difference in AIC and BIC between the two models. Calculate the RMSE and MAE for the training and test datasets.

Classification Problem - Breast Cancer Dataset

Well leverage work weve already performed. Recall in Exercise 5.3.4 we created a logistic regression model on the breast cancer dataset. Well incorporate that work, as well as applying a different algorithm.

Get and prep the data
# libraries
library(caret)  # ML 
library(glmnet)  # regressions
library(rpart)  # decision trees
library(rpart.plot)  # tree plotting
library(tidyverse)  # tidy data and plots

library(scales)  #scaling and other helpers
library(stats)  #AIC/BIC
library(gridExtra)  # Gridded plots

# Set classification thresholds
thresh_1 <- 0.5
thresh_2 <- 0.75
thresh_3 <- 0.9
Build Breast Cancer Model 1: Logistic Regression
Prep Data
# load data
bc_all <- read.csv("/users/werlindo/dropbox/pacp/data/BreastCancerWisconsinDataSet.csv")
# bc_all <-
# read.csv('d:/dropbox/pacp/data/BreastCancerWisconsinDataSet.csv')

# create binarized target
bc_all$target[bc_all$diagnosis == "M"] = 1
bc_all$target[bc_all$diagnosis == "B"] = 0
bc_all$target <- as.factor(bc_all$target)  # This is to force the logistic regression to predict 0/1

# select variables available for training
bc_all <- bc_all[, setdiff(colnames(bc_all), c("diagnosis", "id", "X"))]

# split data into training vs testing; 80%/20%
set.seed(2425)

train <- createDataPartition(bc_all$target, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)

# allocate datasets
bc_train <- bc_all[train, ]
bc_test <- bc_all[-train, ]
Build and Train

Well build the model and see the training results.

# Set up the formula (model form) Know that target is last of 31 columns, so
# take 1:30
bc_formula <- as.formula(paste("target~", paste(names(bc_train[, -(which(names(bc_train) == 
    "target"))]), collapse = "+")))

# Create the data matrix.
X.train <- model.matrix(bc_formula, data = bc_train)
X.test <- model.matrix(bc_formula, data = bc_test)

# Run nonregularized logistic regression
bc_log <- glmnet(X.train, y = bc_train$target, family = "binomial", lambda = 0  #No regularization
)
# Predictions
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Predict the probabilities
bc_log_res_probs <- predict(bc_log, newx = X.train, type = "response")

# logit2prob <- function(logit){ odds <- exp(logit) prob <- odds / (1 +
# odds) return(prob) }

# Create dataframe of predictions
bc_log_res_preds <- data.frame(thresh_1 = as.factor(1 * (bc_log_res_probs > 
    thresh_1)), thresh_2 = as.factor(1 * (bc_log_res_probs > thresh_2)), thresh_3 = as.factor(1 * 
    (bc_log_res_probs > thresh_3)))

Create a confusion matrix for each model using three different cutoff values.

# Confusion Matrices
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Create confusion matrices for the predictions
bc_log_cm_1 <- confusionMatrix(bc_log_res_preds$thresh_1, bc_train$target)
bc_log_cm_2 <- confusionMatrix(bc_log_res_preds$thresh_2, bc_train$target)
bc_log_cm_3 <- confusionMatrix(bc_log_res_preds$thresh_3, bc_train$target)

# Create dataframe of confusion matrices
bc_res_cm_df <- data.frame(as.data.frame.matrix(bc_log_cm_1$table), as.data.frame.matrix(bc_log_cm_2$table), 
    as.data.frame.matrix(bc_log_cm_3$table))

# Some column naming to support final output
bc_res_cm_df <- rownames_to_column(bc_res_cm_df, var = "Prediction")
colnames(bc_res_cm_df)[2:7] <- c("0", "1", "0", "1", "0", "1")

Generate an ROC curve and calculate the AUC for each model.

# ROC Curve

# AUC
# -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Get AUC for each model, put into matrix
a1 <- auc(bc_train$target, as.numeric(bc_log_res_preds$thresh_1))
a2 <- auc(bc_train$target, as.numeric(bc_log_res_preds$thresh_2))
a3 <- auc(bc_train$target, as.numeric(bc_log_res_preds$thresh_3))
aaa <- rbind(a1, a2, a3)

# Create df for eventual display

rownames(bc_log_aucs) <- c()

Build Breast Cancer Model 2: Decision Tree
Build and Train
# Run Modeling/Fit
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------

# Fit a decision tree, method = 'class' ensures the target is treated as a
# categorical variable
bc_dt <- rpart(bc_formula, data = bc_train, method = "class", control = rpart.control(minbucket = 5, 
    cp = 1e-05, maxdepth = 5), parms = list(split = "gini"))

# Plot the tree
rpart.plot(bc_dt)

# Predictions
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Predict the probabilities
bc_dt_res_probs <- predict(bc_dt, newdata = bc_train, type = "prob")

# Create dataframe of predictions
bc_dt_res_preds <- data.frame(thresh_1 = as.factor(1 * (bc_dt_res_probs[, 2] > 
    thresh_1)), thresh_2 = as.factor(1 * (bc_dt_res_probs[, 2] > thresh_2)), 
    thresh_3 = as.factor(1 * (bc_dt_res_probs[, 2] > thresh_3)))

Create a confusion matrix for each model using three different cutoff values.

Well run a toy linear regression with two sets of variables. One with all the variables with the factor variables all binarized; and a smaller one with the factor variables simply removed.

# Set up the formula (model form)
dia_formula <- as.formula(paste("price~", paste(names(dia_train[, -(which(names(dia_train) == 
    "price"))]), collapse = "+")))

# Set up 'smaller' model without binarized variables
sans_bin <- colnames(diamonds[, !(names(diamonds) %in% fctrs) & !(names(diamonds) == 
    "price")])
dia_formula_small <- as.formula(paste("price~", paste(sans_bin, collapse = "+")))


# Create the data matrix.
X_train <- model.matrix(dia_formula, data = dia_train)
X_test <- model.matrix(dia_formula, data = dia_test)

X_train_small <- model.matrix(dia_formula_small, data = dia_train)
X_test_small <- model.matrix(dia_formula_small, data = dia_test)
fit_big <- lm(dia_formula, dia_train)
fit_small <- lm(dia_formula_small, dia_train)

Find the difference in AIC and BIC between the two models.

AIC_big <- AIC(fit_big)
AIC_small <- AIC(fit_small)
AIC_big
## [1] 729556.2
AIC_small
## [1] 753632.3
BIC_big <- BIC(fit_big)
BIC_small <- BIC(fit_small)
BIC_big
## [1] 729773
BIC_small
## [1] 753701.7

Calculate the RMSE and MAE for the training and test datasets.

# Get predictions
pred_big_train <- predict(fit_big)
pred_big_test <- predict(fit_big, newdata = dia_test)
pred_small_train <- predict(fit_small)
pred_small_test <- predict(fit_small, newdata = dia_test_small)

rmse_big_train <- sqrt(sum((pred_big_train - dia_train$price)^2)/dim(dia_train)[1])
rmse_big_test <- sqrt(sum((pred_big_test - dia_test$price)^2)/dim(dia_test)[1])
rmse_small_train <- sqrt(sum((pred_small_train - dia_train$price)^2)/dim(dia_train)[1])
rmse_small_test <- sqrt(sum((pred_small_test - dia_test$price)^2)/dim(dia_test)[1])
# Get predictions
mae_big_train <- sum(abs((pred_big_train - dia_train$price))/dim(dia_train)[1])
mae_big_test <- sum(abs((pred_big_test - dia_test$price))/dim(dia_test)[1])
mae_small_train <- sum(abs((pred_small_train - dia_train$price))/dim(dia_train)[1])
mae_small_test <- sum(abs((pred_small_test - dia_test$price))/dim(dia_test)[1])
# Create vectors for results table contents
model_name <- c("Model 1", "Model 2")
model_desc <- c(paste(dia_formula[2], dia_formula[1], dia_formula[3]), paste(dia_formula_small[2], 
    dia_formula_small[1], dia_formula_small[3]))
v_AIC <- c(AIC_big, AIC_small)
v_BIC <- c(BIC_big, BIC_small)
v_rmse_train <- c(rmse_big_train, rmse_small_train)
v_rmse_test <- c(rmse_big_test, rmse_small_test)
v_mae_train <- c(mae_big_train, mae_small_train)
v_mae_test <- c(mae_big_test, mae_small_test)

# Make df of results
dia_results <- data.frame(model_name, model_desc, v_AIC, v_BIC, v_rmse_train, 
    v_rmse_test, v_mae_train, v_mae_test)
header <- c("Model", "Model Formula", "AIC", "BIC", "RMSE-Train", "RMSE-Test", 
    "MAE-Train", "MAE-Test")
colnames(dia_results) <- header

Model 2 is higher across the board on all validation metrics, which is the hope of the more complex Model 1. So model 1 should be a better fitting model overall.

Comparing RMSEs and MAEs between train and test, theres not a noticeable degradation from train to test, which seems to indicate that the models are not overfitted.

Lets look at the plots of the predictions (test set)!

dia_preds_df <- data.frame(price = dia_test$price, price_mod_1_pred = pred_big_test, 
    price_mod_2_pred = pred_small_test)

plot_mod_1 <- ggplot(dia_preds_df, aes(x = price, y = price_mod_1_pred)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.1, 
    color = "steelblue") + xlim(0, 20000) + ylim(-5000, 20000) + geom_abline(intercept = 0, 
    slope = 1, color = "blue") + ggtitle("Diamonds Prices: Actual vs Predicted | Model 1") + 
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 9, face = "bold"))

plot_mod_2 <- ggplot(dia_preds_df, aes(x = price, y = price_mod_2_pred)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.1, 
    color = "aquamarine4") + xlim(0, 20000) + ylim(-5000, 20000) + geom_abline(intercept = 0, 
    slope = 1, color = "blue") + ggtitle("Diamonds Prices: Actual vs Predicted | Model 2") + 
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 9, face = "bold"))

# colors()
grid.arrange(plot_mod_1, plot_mod_2, ncol = 2)

Makes sense. Model 1 per metrics appears to be better fit; and we can see that visually by how the points of model 1 appear to be tighter around the 45 degree line. Model 2 is interesting in that it seems to produce less negative predicted prices.
